Data Visualization¶

Visualize prosper Loan Data¶

In this project I want to visualize and get some insights about prosper Loan Data because I'm interesed in banking and I want to deploy my anaylsis knowledge on it. Our data related to peer to peer lending which is a way to connect borrower to lenders, the prosper is a platfrom that let people to invest in loans or borrow money. We have 113937 (check the code below) loans in our dataset and 81 columns for each loan.

What is the structure of the dataset?¶

Our dataset has 113937 loans and 81 column which containg the features of the dataset.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in the dataset?¶

The most important things I want to see the the feature that can tell me about the relationship between employee status and borrowing , also the highest profission that borrowes to focus on these profession for the company. For the payments per months for borrowers I'm interested on that. I want to see the relationship between the loan term and loan amount. I'm interested on the relationship between the borrower APR and loan amount

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think the most important feature that I need to check is employee status and borrowing, and the profissions that borrows. I need to see the distribtion of the payments per months for the borrowers I need to plot the feature term with multible features to see the effectance of loan term

#Monthly payments that borroweers made
#the below funstion to create log with the base 10
def log_trans(x, inverse = False):
    if not inverse:
        return np.log10(x)
    else:
        return np.power(10, x)
plt.figure(figsize=[12, 4]);

# simplified actual return formula
prosper_data['Actual_Returns'] = prosper_data.LP_CustomerPayments - prosper_data.LoanOriginalAmount - (prosper_data.LP_ServiceFees + prosper_data.LP_CollectionFees + prosper_data.LP_NetPrincipalLoss)
prosper_data['Actual_Returns'] = (prosper_data.Actual_Returns / prosper_data.LoanOriginalAmount) + 1

def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    default_color = sns.color_palette()[2]
    sns.boxplot(x, y, color = default_color)
